			<h4><a id="comment_link_64212868" name="comment_link_64212868" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23214918&amp;cid=64212868" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64212868)" >Sigh. I&rsquo;m getting old.</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64212868" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64212868); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>4</a>, Insightful)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~hdyoung">hdyoung</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~hdyoung">( 5182939 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64212868">		
		on Sunday February 04, 2024 @11:35AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23214918&amp;cid=64212868">#64212868</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64212868">There&rsquo;s always a million people competing for every top-dog position, and a small few who make it to the top through a combination of talent, hard work, and always a massive helping of luck which they refuse to admit. The result is some tiny number of people wind up on a fast upwards trajectory or at the top, replacing the previous people at the top who are on the decline. Always. ALWAYS.

<br> <br>
And there&rsquo;s always people who claim that this time it&rsquo;s different, and for some reason this shiny new set of top dogs are especially bad, and the &ldquo;new ideology&rdquo; is somehow especially bad. This time around, it&rsquo;s because the interwebs have somehow changed human existence in some sort of futurist-singularity manner.

<br> <br>
No, it&rsquo;s not different. This is an ancient story that repeats over and over. Every generation discovers sex and they think &ldquo;wow this is awesome/interesting/scary/fascinating and it&rsquo;s ALL BRAND NEW LOOK AT WHAT I INVENTED&rdquo; while the oldsters quietly roll their eyes.

<br> <br>
Our current generation of oligarchs are nothing special.

<br> <br>
This will be followed up by several posts that claim the internet has changed human existence and this time around is special. Has the interent changed human existence? Sure. Last century it was the telephone. The century before it was industrialization. Sometime before that it was the printing press or the black plague. For the past thousand years, it&rsquo;s been a constant stream of fundamental disruptions.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64212868">
